üêç TOPIC 7 ‚Äî STRINGS ‚Äî COMPLETE NOTES (PYTHON)
0) What is a String in Python?

A string is a sequence of characters, written inside:

'single quotes' or "double quotes" or """triple quotes""" (multi-line)

Strings are immutable:

You cannot change s[0] directly.

Any ‚Äúmodification‚Äù creates a new string.

Important Properties

Indexing: s[i] (0-based)

Negative indexing: s[-1] = last char

Slicing: s[start:end:step]

Length: len(s)

Membership: 'a' in s

1) Core Operations You‚Äôll Use Everywhere
A) Indexing
s = "python"
print(s[0])   # p
print(s[-1])  # n

B) Slicing (SUPER IMPORTANT)
s = "python"
print(s[1:4])   # yth  (1 to 3)
print(s[:3])    # pyt
print(s[3:])    # hon
print(s[::-1])  # nohtyp (reverse)

C) Looping Through Characters
for ch in s:
    print(ch)

D) Common Built-in / Methods

len(s)

s.upper(), s.lower(), s.title(), s.capitalize()

s.strip(), s.lstrip(), s.rstrip()

s.replace(old, new)

s.count(x)

s.find(x) ‚Üí first index or -1

s.rfind(x) ‚Üí last index or -1

s.startswith(prefix), s.endswith(suffix)

s.isalpha(), s.isdigit(), s.isalnum(), s.islower(), s.isupper()

s.split() (words list)

" ".join(list) (join list into string)

2) Character Classification (for counting tasks)
ASCII value
ord('A')  # 65
chr(65)   # 'A'

Checks (very useful)
ch.isalpha()   # alphabet
ch.isdigit()   # digit
ch.isspace()   # space

Vowels
vowels = "aeiouAEIOU"
if ch in vowels:
    ...

3) Frequency Counting (Most common pattern)
Using Dictionary
freq = {}
for ch in s:
    freq[ch] = freq.get(ch, 0) + 1

Using Counter (shortcut)
from collections import Counter
freq = Counter(s)

4) LEVEL 0 ‚Äî STRING BASICS (01‚Äì25) NOTES
01) Create & Print
s = "Hello"
print(s)

02) Length
print(len(s))

03‚Äì04) First & Last Character
if len(s) > 0:
    print(s[0])
    print(s[-1])

05) Character by character
for ch in s:
    print(ch)

06) Reverse string

Best: slicing

rev = s[::-1]

07‚Äì08) Repeat string
print(s * 2)
print(s * 5)

09) Each char new line

Same as loop.

10) Spaces between characters
print(" ".join(s))

11) ASCII values
for ch in s:
    print(ch, ord(ch))

12‚Äì14) Upper / Lower / Toggle
print(s.upper())
print(s.lower())

toggled = ""
for ch in s:
    if ch.islower():
        toggled += ch.upper()
    else:
        toggled += ch.lower()


(Also exists: s.swapcase())

15) Remove spaces
print(s.replace(" ", ""))

16) Replace spaces with underscore
print(s.replace(" ", "_"))

17‚Äì20) Count chars/spaces/digits/alphabets
chars = len(s)
spaces = sum(1 for ch in s if ch.isspace())
digits = sum(1 for ch in s if ch.isdigit())
alphas = sum(1 for ch in s if ch.isalpha())

21) Check empty string
if s == "":
    ...
# OR
if not s:
    ...

22‚Äì23) Middle char(s)
n = len(s)
if n % 2 == 1:
    print(s[n//2])
else:
    print(s[n//2 - 1], s[n//2])

24) Compare two strings

Lexicographic (dictionary order)

a, b = "abc", "abd"
print(a == b)
print(a < b)

25) Copy string

Strings are immutable, direct assignment is fine

b = a

5) LEVEL 1 ‚Äî VERY BASIC (26‚Äì50) NOTES
26‚Äì30) Count vowels/consonants/upper/lower/special
vowels = "aeiouAEIOU"

v = c = up = low = sp = 0
for ch in s:
    if ch.isalpha():
        if ch in vowels:
            v += 1
        else:
            c += 1
        if ch.isupper():
            up += 1
        if ch.islower():
            low += 1
    else:
        if not ch.isspace():   # if you want space excluded from "special"
            sp += 1

31‚Äì33) Only alphabets / only digits / alphanumeric
s.isalpha()
s.isdigit()
s.isalnum()


‚ö†Ô∏è These return False if string has spaces.

34‚Äì35) Starts with vowel / ends with digit
if s and s[0] in vowels: ...
if s and s[-1].isdigit(): ...

36) Even or odd length
if len(s) % 2 == 0: ...

37) Count occurrences of a character
s.count('a')

38‚Äì39) First/Last occurrence index
s.find('a')     # -1 if not found
s.rfind('a')

40) All occurrences
indexes = []
for i, ch in enumerate(s):
    if ch == target:
        indexes.append(i)

41‚Äì43) Remove first / last / all occurrences
# remove first
i = s.find(target)
if i != -1:
    s2 = s[:i] + s[i+1:]

# remove last
i = s.rfind(target)
if i != -1:
    s2 = s[:i] + s[i+1:]

# remove all
s2 = s.replace(target, "")

44) Replace one char with another
s2 = s.replace(old, new)

45‚Äì47) Replace vowels/digits/consonants
out = []
for ch in s:
    if ch in vowels:
        out.append("*")
    elif ch.isdigit():
        out.append("#")
    elif ch.isalpha():     # consonant
        out.append("$")
    else:
        out.append(ch)
result = "".join(out)

48) Remove duplicate characters (keep first occurrence order)
seen = set()
out = []
for ch in s:
    if ch not in seen:
        seen.add(ch)
        out.append(ch)
result = "".join(out)

49) All characters unique?
unique = len(set(s)) == len(s)

50) Count unique characters
len(set(s))

6) LEVEL 2 ‚Äî BASIC (WORDS & SENTENCES) (51‚Äì75) NOTES
Split into words

Default split removes extra spaces:

words = s.split()

51) Count words
len(words)

52) Print each word new line
for w in words:
    print(w)

53) Words in reverse order
print(" ".join(words[::-1]))

54) Reverse each word individually
rev_words = [w[::-1] for w in words]
print(" ".join(rev_words))

55‚Äì56) Capitalize first letter of each word / Title case
print(" ".join(w.capitalize() for w in words))
print(s.title())


‚ö†Ô∏è title() behaves specially with apostrophes etc.

57) Lowercase word list
lower_words = [w.lower() for w in words]

58‚Äì59) Longest / Shortest word
longest = max(words, key=len)
shortest = min(words, key=len)

60) Length of each word
for w in words:
    print(w, len(w))

61) Frequency of each word
freq = {}
for w in words:
    freq[w] = freq.get(w, 0) + 1

62‚Äì63) Most / least frequent word
most = max(freq, key=freq.get)
least = min(freq, key=freq.get)

64) Remove duplicate words (keep first occurrence)
seen = set()
out = []
for w in words:
    if w not in seen:
        seen.add(w)
        out.append(w)
result = " ".join(out)

65) Replace a word
result = " ".join(new if w == old else w for w in words)

66) Remove a specific word
result = " ".join(w for w in words if w != target)

67) Sentence palindrome (ignore spaces)
t = "".join(ch.lower() for ch in s if not ch.isspace())
is_pal = (t == t[::-1])

68) Count vowels in each word
for w in words:
    count = sum(1 for ch in w if ch in vowels)
    print(w, count)

69‚Äì70) Words starting with vowel / ending with consonant
start_vowel = [w for w in words if w and w[0] in vowels]

end_consonant = [w for w in words
                 if w and w[-1].isalpha() and w[-1] not in vowels]

71) Sort words alphabetically
print(sorted(words, key=str.lower))

72) Sort by length
print(sorted(words, key=len))

73‚Äì74) Common / uncommon words between two sentences
set1 = set(s1.split())
set2 = set(s2.split())
common = set1 & set2
uncommon = set1 ^ set2   # symmetric difference

75) Merge two sentences word by word
w1 = s1.split()
w2 = s2.split()

merged = []
m = min(len(w1), len(w2))
for i in range(m):
    merged.append(w1[i])
    merged.append(w2[i])

merged.extend(w1[m:])
merged.extend(w2[m:])

result = " ".join(merged)

7) LEVEL 3 ‚Äî BASIC+ (PATTERNS & SUBSTRINGS) (76‚Äì90) NOTES
76) Print all substrings

All substrings = all s[i:j] where 0<=i<j<=n

n = len(s)
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(i+1, n+1):
        print(s[i:j])

77) Count total substrings

If length = n, total substrings = n*(n+1)/2

n = len(s)
total = n*(n+1)//2

78) Count palindrome substrings

Brute (O(n^3)):

Generate substring + check palindrome.
Better method:

Expand around center (O(n^2)).

Expand-around-center idea:
Each palindrome expands from:

single center (odd)

gap center (even)

def count_pal_substrings(s):
    n = len(s)
    count = 0

    def expand(l, r):
        nonlocal count
        while l >= 0 and r < n and s[l] == s[r]:
            count += 1
            l -= 1
            r += 1

    for i in range(n):
        expand(i, i)       # odd
        expand(i, i+1)     # even

    return count

79‚Äì80) Longest / shortest palindrome substring

Longest: expand and track max length.

Shortest palindrome substring (usually means length 1 minimum)
If they mean ‚Äúshortest palindrome length > 1‚Äù, then check expansions and track min ‚â• 2.

81) Rotation check

b is rotation of a if:

same length

b is substring of a+a

is_rot = (len(a) == len(b)) and (b in (a + a))

82) Anagram check

Two strings are anagrams if sorted letters same (ignore spaces/case if needed)

def norm(x):
    return sorted(ch.lower() for ch in x if ch.isalpha())

is_ana = norm(a) == norm(b)


Or use frequency dict / Counter.

83) Group anagrams (list of words)

Key = sorted word characters:

from collections import defaultdict

groups = defaultdict(list)
for w in words:
    key = "".join(sorted(w))
    groups[key].append(w)

84) Can string form a palindrome?

Condition:

At most one character has odd frequency.

from collections import Counter
freq = Counter(s)
odd = sum(1 for v in freq.values() if v % 2 == 1)
possible = odd <= 1

85) First non-repeating character
from collections import Counter
freq = Counter(s)
for ch in s:
    if freq[ch] == 1:
        ans = ch
        break
else:
    ans = None

86) First repeating character
seen = set()
for ch in s:
    if ch in seen:
        ans = ch
        break
    seen.add(ch)
else:
    ans = None

87‚Äì88) All repeating chars / freq > 1
from collections import Counter
freq = Counter(s)
repeating = [ch for ch, c in freq.items() if c > 1]

89) Remove adjacent duplicates

Example: "aabbcca" ‚Üí remove adjacent duplicates (keep one each block): "abca"

if not s:
    result = s
else:
    out = [s[0]]
    for i in range(1, len(s)):
        if s[i] != s[i-1]:
            out.append(s[i])
    result = "".join(out)


(Another version removes pairs repeatedly using stack, depends on question statement.)

90) Compress string using Run-Length Encoding (RLE)

Example: "aaabbc" ‚Üí "a3b2c1"

def rle(s):
    if not s:
        return ""
    out = []
    count = 1
    for i in range(1, len(s)):
        if s[i] == s[i-1]:
            count += 1
        else:
            out.append(s[i-1] + str(count))
            count = 1
    out.append(s[-1] + str(count))
    return "".join(out)

8) Most Important ‚ÄúExam Patterns‚Äù You Must Memorize
Pattern A: Count something
count = 0
for ch in s:
    if condition(ch):
        count += 1

Pattern B: Build a new string safely

‚úÖ Use list + join (fast)

out = []
for ch in s:
    out.append(transformed_ch)
result = "".join(out)

Pattern C: Frequency dictionary
freq = {}
for x in items:
    freq[x] = freq.get(x, 0) + 1

Pattern D: Words handling
words = s.split()
# process words
result = " ".join(words)
